\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/ring.dedekind_domain}{Dedekind domain}}
\begin{definition}\label{ring.dedekind_domain}
\uses{nf,nf.ring_of_integers,ring.field,ring.fractional_ideal,ring.ideal,ring.integral_domain,ring.integrally_closed,ring.maximal_ideal,ring.noetherian,ring.prime_ideal}
A \textbf{Dedekind domain} $D$ is a \hyperref[ring.integral_domain]{integral domain} which is not a \hyperref[ring.field]{field} such that

1. $D$ is \hyperref[ring.noetherian]{Noetherian};
2. every non-zero \hyperref[ring.prime_ideal]{prime ideal} is \hyperref[ring.maximal_ideal]{maximal};
3. $D$ is \hyperref[ring.integrally_closed]{integrally closed}.

The \hyperref[nf.ring_of_integers]{ring of integers} of a \hyperref[nf]{number field} is always a Dedekind domain, as is every discrete valuation ring.

In a Dedekind domain, every non-zero \hyperref[ring.ideal]{ideal} $I$ can be written as a product of non-zero \hyperref[ring.prime_ideal]{prime ideals},
$$I=P_1P_2\cdots P_k,$$
and the product is unique up to the order of the factors.  Repeated factors are often grouped, so we write $I=Q_1^{e_1}\cdots Q_g^{e_g}$ where the $Q_i$ are non-zero prime ideals of $D$.

In addition, every \hyperref[ring.fractional_ideal]{fractional ideal} $I$ is invertible in the sense that there exists a fractional ideal $J$ such that $IJ=D$.
\end{definition}
